The Filter First
Before listing anything, every integration must pass this test:

Does this make the environment more powerful, the demo more credible, or the architecture more impressive to an engineer from Google or Meta?

If the answer is "it just adds complexity" — it's overengineering. Everything below passes that filter with a clear reason.

Tier 1 — Non-Negotiable Core Integrations
These make the project technically legitimate. Without them, it's a prototype. With them, it's infrastructure.

1. Playwright (Microsoft)
What it is: A real browser automation framework that controls Chromium, Firefox, or WebKit programmatically.
Why it's essential, not optional:
The entire credibility of this project rests on using a real browser — not a simulated DOM, not a fake HTML renderer. Playwright gives you:

Actual DOM mutations happening in real-time as the agent acts
Real JavaScript execution (SPAs behave exactly as they do in production)
Screenshot capture for visual debugging
Network interception to simulate slow loads, timeouts, API failures

What it replaces: Anything that parses static HTML. If you're not using Playwright or Selenium, judges from Google will immediately flag it as not production-realistic.
Integration point: Every agent action (click, type, scroll) maps directly to a Playwright command executed on a live Chromium instance.

2. Docker
What it is: Containerization — each generated website runs in its own isolated container.
Why this is architecture, not decoration:
Every training episode generates a new React app. Without Docker, these apps collide — shared ports, shared state, environment bleed. With Docker:

Each episode spins up a fresh container with a freshly generated React app
Episode ends → container destroyed → zero state leakage between episodes
You can run 10 parallel training episodes simultaneously on the same machine
The environment is reproducible — any judge can run it on their laptop

The demo value: When you say "each episode is a containerized, fully functional web application spun up fresh and destroyed after," — every engineer in the room understands the discipline that implies.

3. Weights & Biases (W&B)
What it is: Experiment tracking and visualization platform used by every serious ML team.
Why this is critical for a hackathon specifically:
W&B gives you a live dashboard during your demo showing:

Agent success rate climbing over training episodes in real-time
Task completion broken down by step (where exactly does the agent fail most?)
Comparison runs: baseline agent vs. your agent on the same DOM variants
Video recordings of agent episodes — you can literally replay the agent booking a flight

The killer moment in the demo:
Pull up the W&B dashboard. Show a graph with two lines — standard web agent (flat, ~30% success) and your agent (climbing to ~90%). Point to the x-axis. Say: "This is training episodes. This is where it learned to stop memorizing and start understanding."
That visual alone wins the room.

Tier 2 — High Signal Integrations
These add one specific capability that makes the project meaningfully more powerful.

4. LiteLLM + Any LLM (Claude/GPT-4)
What it is: A lightweight unified API to call any LLM. LiteLLM lets you swap between Claude, GPT-4, Gemini with one line change.
Exactly one place to use this — don't overuse it:
Use an LLM solely to convert natural language task instructions into structured task graphs.
User says: "Book me a train to Mumbai, 2AC, this Saturday"

LLM converts to:
{
  task_type: "travel_booking",
  steps: ["select_origin", "select_destination", 
          "select_date", "select_class", "confirm"],
  parameters: {
    destination: "Mumbai",
    class: "2AC",
    date: "this_saturday"
  }
}
The RL agent then operates on this structured graph — it never processes raw natural language. The LLM handles instruction parsing. The RL agent handles navigation. Clean separation of responsibilities.
Why this matters to judges: It directly mirrors how real production web agent systems are architected — LLM as planner, RL/execution engine as actor. You're not bolting on an LLM for show. You're demonstrating you understand the actual architecture.

5. WebArena / Mind2Web Benchmark Integration
What it is: WebArena is an existing open-source benchmark for evaluating web agents on real-world tasks. Mind2Web is a dataset of real human web navigation traces from 137 real websites.
Why this is a credibility multiplier:
Without this, your evaluation is self-reported — "our agent gets 90% on our own tests." Judges will discount it.
With this: "Our agent achieves X% on the WebArena benchmark, compared to the current state-of-the-art of Y%."
That's a citation. That's a number judges from Google and Meta can verify. That turns a hackathon project into something that sits in the same sentence as published research.
Integration effort: WebArena is open source on GitHub. You run your trained agent on their task suite and report the number. One afternoon of work for enormous credibility gain.

6. Redis
What it is: In-memory key-value store. Extremely fast read/write — microsecond latency.
Exactly one job: DOM state caching between agent steps.
When the agent takes an action, the DOM updates. Parsing the entire DOM tree from scratch every step is slow — hundreds of milliseconds per step. Redis caches the current DOM graph state so between actions, the agent reads from memory, not from a fresh DOM parse.
The practical impact: Training speed increases significantly. More episodes per hour = better trained agent = better demo results. This is invisible to the audience but critical to actually shipping a working project in hackathon time.

